President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring October 11, 2013, as General Pulaski Memorial Day. This day is dedicated to honoring the memory and sacrifice of Brigadier General Casimir Pulaski, a Polish-born hero of the American Revolutionary War. Pulaski played a crucial role in securing America's independence and gave his life in defense of freedom. The proclamation recognizes Pulaski's bravery on the battlefield and his contributions to the American cavalry. It also acknowledges the contributions of Polish-Americans throughout history and highlights the enduring friendship between the United States and Poland. The proclamation encourages Americans to commemorate this day by participating in programs and activities that pay tribute to Pulaski and honor all those who defend the freedom of the nation.